50|$|At the {{macro-economic}} level, <b>deleveraging</b> of {{an economy}} refers to the simultaneous reduction of debt levels in multiple sectors, including private sectors and the government sector. It is usually measured as a decline of the total debt to GDP ratio in the national account. The <b>deleveraging</b> {{of an economy}} following a financial crisis has significant macro-economic consequences and {{is often associated with}} severe recessions.|$|E
50|$|Based on this {{identification}} of <b>deleveraging</b> and Carmen Reinhart and Kenneth Rogoff’s definition for major episodes of financial crisis, {{it is found}} that almost every major financial crisis during the period of study has been followed by a period of <b>deleveraging.</b> After the 2008 financial crisis, economists expected <b>deleveraging</b> to occur globally. Instead the total debt in all nations combined increased by $57 trillion from 2007 to 2015 and government debt increased by $25 trillion. According to the McKinsey Global Institute, from 2007 to 2015, five developing nations and zero advanced ones reduced their debt-to-GDP ratio and 14 countries increased it by 50 percent or more. As of 2015, the ratio of debt to gross domestic product globally is 17 percent.|$|E
